`crates/steno/src/bin/` holds three independent CLI entry points that all consume the `steno` library's `parse_source` → `expand_dict` → build/measure pipeline against the same input file, `dict.steno` at the workspace root. Nothing here is a library dependency of anything else in the codebase — these are terminal build/diagnostic tools invoked by name (`cargo run --bin <name>`), and downstream consumers (the Plover profiles, the nvim plugin) read only their emitted `out/*.json` files, never this code.

All three binaries share the same fragile root-resolution convention: `CARGO_MANIFEST_DIR/../..`, which is only correct because each binary lives at `crates/steno/src/bin/`. Moving any of them — or the crate itself — breaks the path to `dict.steno` and `out/` silently (no compile error, just wrong/missing files at runtime). Any change to `expand_dict`'s signature, its optional param, or `parse_source`/`build_*`/`to_json` in the `steno` lib ripples into all three files simultaneously since each calls the same chain directly.

`build_dict.rs` is the production build for Plover (`plain.json` + `smart.json`), `build_nvim.rs` is the production build for the nvim plugin (`plover-keys.json` + `snippets.json`), and `measure.rs` is a read-only diagnostic that never writes files, instead printing a size matrix across generic-arg-pool and param-shape combinations for manual comparison. All three independently implement the same collision-guard idiom: dedupe via `BTreeSet`, guard/abort before any file write, so a colliding stroke never produces a partially-updated `out/` — this convention is duplicated three times rather than shared, so a fix to one guard's behavior won't propagate to the others.

`measure.rs` additionally carries a hand-maintained `NOPARAM` table of hardcoded strokes that must be kept in sync with whatever function-shape entries currently exist in `dict.steno`; a rename or removal there silently degrades measurement accuracy without any error.